{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f4237638-136e-457f-b9a3-3e445a1c247d","content":"PID 12345 isn't running on this machine, so I can't inspect it directly. Here's how to diagnose and configure on **your** system:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Determine the runtime\n\n```bash\n# If CoreCLR, you'll see libcoreclr.so in the process memory maps:\ngrep -qE 'libcoreclr\\.so' /proc/12345/maps && echo \"CoreCLR\" || echo \"Likely NativeAOT\"\n\n# Double-check — NativeAOT binaries are statically linked, so:\nfile $(readlink -f /proc/12345/exe)\n# CoreCLR → \"ELF … dynamically linked\"\n# NativeAOT → \"ELF … statically linked\" (or dynamically linked but no libcoreclr)\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2a. Configure dumps for **CoreCLR**\n\nCoreCLR has its own dump environment variables:\n\n```bash\n# In the app's environment (e.g. systemd unit or shell):\nexport DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1          # Enable automatic dumps on crash\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4            # 4 = Full heap dump (1=Mini, 2=WithHeap, 3=Triage, 4=Full)\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=\"/tmp/dumps/coredump.%p.%t\"   # %p=PID, %t=timestamp\nmkdir -p /tmp/dumps\n```\n\nAlternatively, use `createdump` (ships with the runtime):\n\n```bash\n# Find it:\nfind /usr/share/dotnet -name createdump 2>/dev/null\n# Manual capture:\n/usr/share/dotnet/shared/Microsoft.NETCore.App/10.*/createdump 12345\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2b. Configure dumps for **NativeAOT**\n\nNativeAOT does **not** use `createdump` or the `DOTNET_Dbg*` variables. It relies on the **OS kernel** core dump mechanism:\n\n```bash\n# Enable kernel core dumps:\nulimit -c unlimited\n\n# Configure the dump path via kernel pattern:\nsudo sysctl -w kernel.core_pattern=\"/tmp/dumps/core.%e.%p.%t\"\nsudo mkdir -p /tmp/dumps\n\n# Or if using systemd-coredump (common on modern distros):\ncoredumpctl list   # verify it's active\n```\n\nFor **systemd services**, also add to the unit file:\n\n```ini\n[Service]\nLimitCORE=infinity\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. If using systemd (works for both runtimes)\n\n```ini\n# /etc/systemd/system/myapp.service\n[Service]\nExecStart=/path/to/myapp\nLimitCORE=infinity\n# For CoreCLR only:\nEnvironment=DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\nEnvironment=DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4\nEnvironment=DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/tmp/dumps/coredump.%p.%t\n```\n\n```bash\nsudo systemctl daemon-reload && sudo systemctl restart myapp\n```\n\n---\n\n**TL;DR:** Run the `grep` command from step 1 to identify your runtime. CoreCLR → use `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump`. NativeAOT → use `ulimit -c unlimited` + `kernel.core_pattern`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"27cdfd4c-9c48-43e4-9c64-e24d020aaffa","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The process doesn't exist on this machine. That's expected — it's on the user's system. Let me give them the diagnostic steps and configuration guidance instead.","outputTokens":901,"requestId":"2C4D:1E67:29F8D9:320AF1:69F94E7F"},"id":"403689a7-bdaf-4dcd-a341-ef7e27c9d8d9","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:57:38.073Z","parentId":"2338be3a-43a9-41c1-8f91-84a9c0811d6d"}
